"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911188","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-04","<p>Energy suppliers that are obligated to participate in the Warm Home Discount scheme cover 94% of the market for domestic customers. Suppliers that are not obligated under the scheme can volunteer to provide rebates to the Core Group. Last winter, three suppliers volunteered under the scheme.</p><p> </p><p>We estimate that the number of pensioners beyond those 18 suppliers that would have been automatically eligible for Warm Home Discount last winter under the Core Group is roughly 60,000, of the roughly 1.4 million Pension Credit Guaranteed Credit recipients who would be automatically eligible if they held an account with a participating supplier.</p><p> </p><p>There is a set spending envelope for Warm Home Discount and increasing the number of obligated suppliers would not in itself increase the number of households receiving the rebate. We have recently completed a consultation on the next phase of Warm Home Discount, including the obligation thresholds, and are currently reviewing the responses.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","147937","2018-06-04T14:39:23.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911188/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911188/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-24","Pensioners: Warm Home Discount Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of whether some pensioners are missing out on the Warm Home Discount Scheme as a result of being customers of a supplier with fewer than 250,000 customers.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","147936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911189","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-06-04","<p>Energy suppliers that are obligated to participate in the Warm Home Discount scheme cover 94% of the market for domestic customers. Suppliers that are not obligated under the scheme can volunteer to provide rebates to the Core Group. Last winter, three suppliers volunteered under the scheme.</p><p> </p><p>We estimate that the number of pensioners beyond those 18 suppliers that would have been automatically eligible for Warm Home Discount last winter under the Core Group is roughly 60,000, of the roughly 1.4 million Pension Credit Guaranteed Credit recipients who would be automatically eligible if they held an account with a participating supplier.</p><p> </p><p>There is a set spending envelope for Warm Home Discount and increasing the number of obligated suppliers would not in itself increase the number of households receiving the rebate. We have recently completed a consultation on the next phase of Warm Home Discount, including the obligation thresholds, and are currently reviewing the responses.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","147936","2018-06-04T14:39:23.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911189/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911189/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-24","Warm Home Discount Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the number of people eligible for the Warm Home Discount Scheme who will not receive that discount in 2018-19 because they are customers of an energy supplier with fewer than 250,000 customers.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","147937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911190","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-04","<p>The Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition (SACN) undertakes a risk assessment to determine whether to revise its advice either because of a need identified through horizon scanning or at the request of government. The SACN undertakes all risk assessment in line with its framework for the evaluation of evidence. The SACN’s risk assessments take account of evidence on intake and need in relation to health outcomes considered to be of key public health concern.</p><p> </p><p>The SACN undertakes nutritional risk assessment on a case by case basis in relation to need – this is usually either because of a need identified through horizon scanning or at the request of government. The SACN has no plans to develop specific additional advice on supplement use.</p><p> </p><p>The SACN has made supplementation recommendations in relation to vitamin D and folic acid. Which are available at the following links:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sacn-vitamin-d-and-health-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sacn-vitamin-d-and-health-report</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/folic-acid-updated-sacn-recommendations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/folic-acid-updated-sacn-recommendations</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","147851 ; 147852","2018-06-04T13:56:29.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911190/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911190/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-24","Scientific Advisory Committee On Nutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what factors the Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition takes into account when determining whether to revise its advice on any aspect of nutritional supplementation.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","147850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911191","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-04","<p>The Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition (SACN) undertakes a risk assessment to determine whether to revise its advice either because of a need identified through horizon scanning or at the request of government. The SACN undertakes all risk assessment in line with its framework for the evaluation of evidence. The SACN’s risk assessments take account of evidence on intake and need in relation to health outcomes considered to be of key public health concern.</p><p> </p><p>The SACN undertakes nutritional risk assessment on a case by case basis in relation to need – this is usually either because of a need identified through horizon scanning or at the request of government. The SACN has no plans to develop specific additional advice on supplement use.</p><p> </p><p>The SACN has made supplementation recommendations in relation to vitamin D and folic acid. Which are available at the following links:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sacn-vitamin-d-and-health-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sacn-vitamin-d-and-health-report</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/folic-acid-updated-sacn-recommendations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/folic-acid-updated-sacn-recommendations</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","147850 ; 147852","2018-06-04T13:56:29.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911191/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911191/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-24","Scientific Advisory Committee On Nutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will list all the recommendations the Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition has issued in respect of nutritional supplements by (a) nutritional supplement, (b) when the recommendation was last reviewed in each case and (c) what triggered the last review in the case of each supplement; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","147851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911192","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-04","<p>The Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition (SACN) undertakes a risk assessment to determine whether to revise its advice either because of a need identified through horizon scanning or at the request of government. The SACN undertakes all risk assessment in line with its framework for the evaluation of evidence. The SACN’s risk assessments take account of evidence on intake and need in relation to health outcomes considered to be of key public health concern.</p><p> </p><p>The SACN undertakes nutritional risk assessment on a case by case basis in relation to need – this is usually either because of a need identified through horizon scanning or at the request of government. The SACN has no plans to develop specific additional advice on supplement use.</p><p> </p><p>The SACN has made supplementation recommendations in relation to vitamin D and folic acid. Which are available at the following links:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sacn-vitamin-d-and-health-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sacn-vitamin-d-and-health-report</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/folic-acid-updated-sacn-recommendations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/folic-acid-updated-sacn-recommendations</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","147850 ; 147851","2018-06-04T13:56:29.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911192/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911192/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-24","Scientific Advisory Committee On Nutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans the Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition has to develop additional advice on the use of food supplements by nutrient.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","147852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911193","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-04","<p>Public Health England advice on vitamin D supplements recognises that in spring and summer, the majority of the population get enough vitamin D through sunlight on the skin and a healthy, balanced diet. The advice from the Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition was unable to take account of skin synthesis of vitamin D.</p><p> </p><p>During autumn and winter everyone will need to rely on dietary sources of vitamin D. Vitamin D intake and status is measured through the United Kingdom National Diet and Nutrition Survey rolling programme.</p><p> </p><p>Clear advice to the public continues to be communicated via the NHS Choices website at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/vitamins-and-minerals/vitamin-d/" target="_blank">https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/vitamins-and-minerals/vitamin-d/</a></p><p> </p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence has produced guidance on increasing vitamin D supplement use among population groups at risk of vitamin D deficiency, which is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ph56" target="_blank">https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ph56</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-04T14:07:05.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911193/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911193/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-24","Scientific Advisory Committee On Nutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the revised advice issued by the Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition in July 2016 on vitamin D, for what reasons Public Health England limited the application of the advice to autumn and winter only; what steps he has taken to monitor the effect of that change in the advice on the health of the population; what steps have been taken to make the public aware of that advice; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","147853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911194","Women and Equalities","false","2018-06-20","<p>This survey is intended to help us understand how many unmarried people in an opposite-sex relationship may enter into a civil partnership if the option was open to them.</p><p>Creating a new survey mechanism to ask a small number of questions would have been disproportionately time-consuming and would not have been efficient, so it was decided to use an existing polling structure.</p><p>The ONS Opinions and Lifestyle survey offered the only regular omnibus survey of the general population using a random sample, rather than drawing on pre-screened panels.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-06-20T16:45:03.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911194/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911194/answer",,,,,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2018-05-24","Civil Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, with reference to the command paper, Future operation of Civil Partnerships, Cm. 9606, published in May 2018, what specifications her Department issued on the opinion polling to be conducted when appointing an organisation to undertake opinion polling on demand for extending civil partnerships; and for what reasons the Office for National Statistics was so appointed.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","147775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911195","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-04","<p>We plan to publish a Government response to the consultation on the Green Paper ahead of summer recess.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-06-04T14:18:24.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911195/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911195/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-24","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to Transforming Children and Young People’s Mental Health Provision: a Green Paper, jointly published by his Department and the Department for Education, when the Government plans to publish its response to the consultation on that Green Paper.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","147776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911196","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-04","<p>The inclusion of mobile concrete batching plant, alongside a number of other formerly-exempt vehicles types, in statutory goods vehicle testing from 20 May 2018 does not change the legal weight limits applicable to these vehicles.</p><p>The ‘special types’ rules, which permit certain vehicle types to operate outside the standard weight limits, are generally used to enable the carriage of equipment and indivisible loads which for engineering reasons cannot feasibly comply with the standard rules, and not because of economic or financial considerations. To apply these rules to divisible loads would represent a significant departure from precedent, could lead to demands for other vehicle types to be afforded similar treatment and would therefore require an exceptionally compelling case.</p><p>There is nothing to indicate that mobile batching plant, which carries a divisible load, cannot be feasibly operated within the standard legal weight limits.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-06-04T14:21:51.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911196/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911196/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-24","Large Goods Vehicles: Weight Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to his Department's letter entitled Regulation of mobile concrete batching plant – decision on operating weight arrangements, published on 5 April 2018, what the evidential basis was for his Department's decision that there was no compelling case for amending regulations to permit mobile batching concrete plants (MCBPs) to continue to operate outside standard legal gross vehicle weight limits after the inclusion of MCBPs within statutory goods vehicle testing from 20 May 2018.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","147972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911197","Cabinet Office","false","2018-06-07","<p>The Cabinet Office Implementation Unit supports the Prime Minister by tracking the delivery of the Government's programme​. ​It is ​not the practice of the Government to disclose internal advice to Ministers.</p><p> </p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-06-07T14:20:33.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911197/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911197/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-05-24","Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish the report from 2017 on the rise in the number of care applications which was conducted by the Cabinet Office Implementation Unit.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","147777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911198","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-04","<p>The Department does not in general conduct impact assessments on the application of existing legal requirements, and has no plans to do so in this case.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-06-04T14:24:24.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911198/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/911198/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-24","Large Goods Vehicles: Weight Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to conduct an assessment of the effect of not permitting mobile batching concrete plants to continue to operate outside standard legal gross vehicle weight limits on (a) the economy and (b) businesses.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","147973"
