"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910241","Department for Education","false","2018-06-05","<p>The department and the academy trust responsible for the Isle of Wight Studio School – the Inspire Academy Trust – both agree that the school is not viable. The school was established to be a provision for 14 to 19 year olds (years 10 to 13); however, pupil numbers are currently at only 40% of capacity, providing education for 14 to 16 year olds only (years 10 and 11).</p><p> </p><p>Ormiston Academies Trust submitted a bid for emergency school improvement funding, to support to the current year 10 and 11 cohorts until 2019. Ormiston later withdrew this application, as they were not able to demonstrate that their support would be sustainable long-term.</p><p> </p><p>On 28 February 2018, Inspire Academy Trust informed the Regional Schools Commissioner of its proposal to close the Isle of Wight Studio School. Prior to making an in principle decision for closure, the department explored alternative options for the future of the school. The Regional Schools Commissioner and the Inspire Academy Trust spoke to potential alternative trusts about sponsoring the studio school. However, the long-term viability of the school presented challenges to finding a trust willing to proceed.</p><p> </p><p>The department is considering responses to the listening period, which ended on 22 May. A final decision on the closure of the school will be made in light of these, and to ensure that the educational provision on the island is of the highest quality and provides genuine value.</p><p> </p><p>Revenue and capital costs associated with the studio schools are published on GOV.UK at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/revenue-spending-on-open-and-withdrawn-utcs-and-studio-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/revenue-spending-on-open-and-withdrawn-utcs-and-studio-schools</a> and <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-funding-for-open-free-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/capital-funding-for-open-free-schools</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Additional, updated revenue and capital costs for individual free schools, university technical colleges and studio schools are due to be published in the coming months.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","147458 ; 147459 ; 147460 ; 147461 ; 147462 ; 147907","2018-06-05T17:02:18.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910241/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910241/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910241/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-23","Isle of Wight Studio School: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reasons his Department did not allow the Isle of Wight college and CECAMM to take over the Studio School Isle of Wight.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","147463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910242","Home Office","false","2018-06-05","<p>The Home Office commissions The Salvation Army to provide a comprehensive package of support to potential victims of modern slavery referred into the National Referral Mechanism. This is delivered through a network of support providers throughout England and Wales.</p><p>Whilst we consider the implication of the Court of Appeal judgment in the case of (PK (Ghana) v SSHD), interim guidance has been issued to caseworkers to put on hold any refusals of discretionary leave to remain (DL) decisions for confirmed victims of modern slavery.</p><p>Grants of discretionary leave are continuing. This guidance is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/interim-operation-guidance-discretionary-leave-for-victims-of-modern-slavery" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/interim-operation-guidance-discretionary-leave-for-victims-of-modern-slavery</a></p><p>In line with standard practice, support providers under the Victim Care Contract can seek an extension of support for confirmed victims who are awaiting a discretionary leave decision.</p><p>This service has been designed to accommodate both potential increases in the numbers of people requiring support and to provide extensions of care for those already in the system for as long as it is required.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-06-05T14:10:39.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910242/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910242/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910242/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what provision he has made to deal with the potential increase in demand for capacity resulting from (a) victims having their support extended due to the interim guidance given as a result of the PK (Ghana) decision and (b) continued referrals into the National Referral Mechanism as a result of the PK (Ghana) decision; and whether additional financial resources have been made available for such potential increases.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","147349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910243","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-04","<p>No assessment has been made of the effectiveness of baby boxes in Scotland, and we have no plans to formally extend such provision to England.</p><p> </p><p>Unicef UK and the Lullaby Trust have provided statements regarding what considerations should be made when delivering such schemes to ensure that they comply with safety standards and cause no harm to babies and their parents. The statements can be accessed at the following links:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.unicef.org.uk/babyfriendly/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2017/11/Statement-on-Baby-Box-Schemes-Unicef-UK-Baby-Friendly-Initiative.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.unicef.org.uk/babyfriendly/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2017/11/Statement-on-Baby-Box-Schemes-Unicef-UK-Baby-Friendly-Initiative.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.lullabytrust.org.uk/are-baby-boxes-safe-to-sleep-baby/" target="_blank">https://www.lullabytrust.org.uk/are-baby-boxes-safe-to-sleep-baby/</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-06-04T13:50:21.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910243/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910243/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910243/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-23","Babies: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of baby boxes in Scotland; and whether his Department has plans to extend such provision to England.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","147350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910244","Treasury","false","2018-06-07","<p>In the period from the beginning of April 2016 to end March 2017 HMRC distributed a total of 743,733 packs.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-06-07T13:40:28.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910244/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910244/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910244/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-23","Child Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exechequer, how many new parents received bounty packs with paperwork containing information on applying for child benefit in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","147351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910245","Treasury","false","2018-06-04","<p>Statistics on the Company Share Options Plans and Enterprise Management Incentives schemes are published in Tables 6.4 and 6.6 of the Employee Share Schemes Statistics publication: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/employee-share-schemes-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/employee-share-schemes-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>Estimates are updated annually and the latest year for which data is available is 2015/16. Estimates for 2016/17 will be published in due course.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","147477","2018-06-04T14:58:53.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910245/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910245/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910245/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-23","Enterprise Management Incentives: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) businesses and (b) people claimed income tax relief through the Enterprise Management Incentives scheme in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","147476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910246","Treasury","false","2018-06-04","<p>Statistics on the Company Share Options Plans and Enterprise Management Incentives schemes are published in Tables 6.4 and 6.6 of the Employee Share Schemes Statistics publication: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/employee-share-schemes-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/employee-share-schemes-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>Estimates are updated annually and the latest year for which data is available is 2015/16. Estimates for 2016/17 will be published in due course.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","147476","2018-06-04T14:58:53.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910246/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910246/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910246/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-23","Business: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many businesses claimed income tax relief through the Approved Company Share Options Plans in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","147477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910247","Treasury","false","2018-06-04","<p>HMRC publishes statistics on the number of individuals claiming income tax relief on investments in Venture Capital Trusts here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/venture-capital-trusts-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/venture-capital-trusts-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>The latest release of these statistics was published in December 2017 and includes data up to 2015-16. Statistics for 2016-17 will be published later this year.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC publishes statistics on the number of individuals claiming income tax relief through the Enterprise Investment Scheme and Seed Enterprise Investment Scheme here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/enterprise-investment-scheme-and-seed-enterprise-investment-scheme-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/enterprise-investment-scheme-and-seed-enterprise-investment-scheme-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>The latest release of these statistics was published in October 2017 and includes data up to 2015-16. Statistics for 2016-17 will be published on 31 May 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Only individuals are eligible to claim tax relief on investments under the schemes.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","147479","2018-06-04T14:56:09.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910247/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910247/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910247/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-23","Venture Capital Trusts: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) businesses and (b) people claimed income tax relief through Venture Capital Trusts in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","147478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910248","Treasury","false","2018-06-04","<p>HMRC publishes statistics on the number of individuals claiming income tax relief on investments in Venture Capital Trusts here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/venture-capital-trusts-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/venture-capital-trusts-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>The latest release of these statistics was published in December 2017 and includes data up to 2015-16. Statistics for 2016-17 will be published later this year.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC publishes statistics on the number of individuals claiming income tax relief through the Enterprise Investment Scheme and Seed Enterprise Investment Scheme here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/enterprise-investment-scheme-and-seed-enterprise-investment-scheme-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/enterprise-investment-scheme-and-seed-enterprise-investment-scheme-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>The latest release of these statistics was published in October 2017 and includes data up to 2015-16. Statistics for 2016-17 will be published on 31 May 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Only individuals are eligible to claim tax relief on investments under the schemes.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","147478","2018-06-04T14:56:09.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910248/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910248/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910248/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-23","Seed Enterprise Investment Scheme: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) businesses and (b) people claimed income tax relief through the Seed Enterprise Investment Scheme in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","147479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910249","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-04","<p>Agriculture is a devolved responsibility, and it is the Government’s intention that each administration has the freedom to design policies that support the individual characteristics of their agricultural industries and unique landscapes.</p><p>The Government has committed to work closely with the Devolved Administrations and stakeholders to deliver an approach that works for the whole of the UK and reflects the individual needs of Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland; subject to where common frameworks may be necessary.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-06-04T12:44:01.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910249/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910249/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910249/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-23","Agriculture: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what support his Department has provided to the devolved administration in Edinburgh to devise agricultural policies for the period after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Luke Graham","Ochil and South Perthshire","Luke Graham","147508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910250","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-07","<p>Responsibility for policy, and any related initiatives, to support rural communities in Scotland rests with the Scottish Government.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-06-07T11:39:57.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910250/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910250/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910250/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-23","Rural Areas: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what new initiatives his Department has implemented to support rural communities in Scotland in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Luke Graham","Ochil and South Perthshire","Luke Graham","147509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910251","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-04","<p>Universal Credit provides us with the opportunity to support people to progress, and we are building the evidence about what works, such as through a large-scale Randomised Control Trial.</p><p> </p><p>This trial tested different degrees of in-work support and conditionality to support people to progress. Through targeted work coach support, requirements were agreed to support individuals to take reasonable action to help them to earn more where appropriate. The trial finished on 31 March 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The following link provides figures for the data collected so far on sanctions for in work claimants:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/in-work-progression-trial-update-april-2015-to-october-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/in-work-progression-trial-update-april-2015-to-october-2016</a></p><p> </p><p>This shows that up to the end of October 2016, 319 sanctions had been applied to 15,455 trial participants: approximately 2%. This means that 98% of all trial participants were not sanctioned. The trial started on 20 April 2015, so the 319 sanctions cover the time period from the start of the trial to the end of October 2016. The majority of the sanctions that were applied were low level: 92% of all sanctions applied were for failing to attend meetings or phone calls without good reason.</p><p> </p><p>Further statistical information regarding the number of sanctions and suspensions for in-work claimants within the Randomised Control Trial will be published in Autumn 2018.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-06-04T13:45:04.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910251/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910251/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910251/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-23","Universal Credit: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of universal credit claimants in employment that have been sanctioned in the most recent three months for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","147352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910252","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-06-04","<p>The terms of reference, as published, remain correct. They set out that badger culling is within the scope of the Bovine TB strategy review. They explain that this is not narrowly a review of culling but of the whole Bovine TB strategy, of which culling is just one part. They also make clear the review will not revisit the rationale for current interventions deployed to tackle the disease.</p><p> </p><p>The review of the Bovine TB strategy is forward looking and will consider what steps can be taken to improve, enhance or accelerate interventions to achieve the eradication of bovine TB.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-06-04T11:17:32.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910252/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910252/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910252/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-23","Bovine Tuberculosis: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, for what reason the terms of reference on his Department's website for the 2018 bovine tuberculosis strategy review have not been updated to reflect the fact that the review is planned to consider all areas of the existing bovine TB strategy including badger culling.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","147310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910253","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-04","<p>A list of visits made by Ministers over the past 18 months to private hospitals and the subject matter of those visits is shown in the following table.</p><p><br> A special adviser has visited the Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston and Vanderbilt University Medical Centre, Nashville to discuss technology and innovation.</p><p> </p><p>No other Ministers or Special Advisers have undertaken such visits during the past 18 months.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Title of Minister</p></td><td><p>Private Hospital</p></td><td><p>Subject of Visit</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>The Parliamentary Under Secretary of State (Jackie Doyle-Price)</p></td><td><p>Newton House, Independent Hospital, Blackpool.</p></td><td><p>To visit locked rehabilitation services, and meet staff and service users</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="7"><p>The former Minister of State (Mr Philip Dunne MP)</p></td><td><p>Texas Medical Centre, Texas, USA</p></td><td rowspan="7"><p>Tour and discussion on service delivery and innovation</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Texas Children’s hospital, Texas, USA</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>MD Anderson Cancer Centre, Texas, USA</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Visit to Brigham and Women’s hospital, Boston, USA</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Spaulding Rehabilitation hospital, Boston, USA</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Children’s Hospital, Boston, USA</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Vanderbilt University medical centre, Nashville, USA</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-06-04T15:48:29.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910253/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910253/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910253/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-23","Hospitals: Domestic Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 23 May 2018 to Question 145570, if he will publish a list of which private hospitals (a) Ministers and (b) Special Advisers of his Department have visited in each of the last 18 months; and what the subjects of those visits were for each of those hospitals so listed.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","147449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910254","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-06-04","<p>The Universal Credit Extended Gateway Evaluation provided evidence that indicated that a large majority of Universal Credit claimants are comfortable managing their budgets.</p><p> </p><p>The report can be accessed at:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/481865/universal-credit-extended-gateway-evaluation.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/481865/universal-credit-extended-gateway-evaluation.pdf</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-06-04T13:10:25.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910254/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910254/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910254/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-23","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 7537, what the evidential basis is for the research that showed that the majority of universal credit claimants are comfortable managing their budgets.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","147353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910255","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-08","<p>This information is not held centrally. Information on the number of finished admission episodes (FAEs) in secondary care (activity in English National Health Service hospitals and English NHS-commissioned activity in the independent sector) with a primary diagnosis for atrial fibrillation and flutter between 2012/13 and 2016/17, and for atrial fibrillation only for 2016-17, is shown in the following table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>98,503</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>100,991</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>102,569</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>107,895</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>109,431</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Note:</p><p> </p><p>An FAE is the first period of admitted patient care under one consultant within one healthcare provider. FAEs are counted against the year or month in which the admission episode finishes. Admissions do not represent the number of patients, as a person may have more than one admission within the period. The primary diagnosis refers to the main reason why the patient was admitted to hospital.</p><p> </p><p>The number of FAEs in secondary care with a primary diagnosis for atrial fibrillation only in 2016/17 is 34,517. Atrial fibrillation-only FAE data (i.e. not including atrial flutter FAE data as well) is not available prior to 2016/17 as this information was not separately recorded by NHS Digital prior to that year.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-08T10:49:55.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910255/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910255/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910255/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-23","Atrial Fibrillation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many people have received a diagnosis of atrial fibrillation in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","147438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910256","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-05","<p>This information is not available.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-05T13:56:02.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910256/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910256/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910256/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-23","Persistent Postural-Perceptual Dizziness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many people have received a diagnosis of persistent postural-perceptual dizziness in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","147439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910257","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-05","<p>Cosmetic products, which include sunscreens, are regulated and must be safe for human health when used under normal or reasonably foreseeable conditions of use.</p><p> </p><p>Given the known risks from sunburn and the potential for skin cancer, it is important to take appropriate sun safety precautions including use of sun cream. Advice to the general population on sun protection may be found on NHS Choices at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/live-well/healthy-body/sunscreen-and-sun-safety/" target="_blank">https://www.nhs.uk/live-well/healthy-body/sunscreen-and-sun-safety/</a></p><p> </p><p>Public Health England advises that the risks from ultraviolet exposure as a result of not using sun cream will be greater than any potential risk from exposure to chemicals in these products and continued use of these products is recommended.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-05T13:50:30.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910257/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910257/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910257/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-23","Sunscreens: Health Hazards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department provides guidance for patients on the use of sun cream containing chemicals that may affect breast tissue.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","147440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910258","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-05","<p>As part of our Childhood Obesity Plan we have seen some good progress on sugar reduction.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England’s (PHE) sugar reduction programme challenges industry to reduce sugar by 20% by 2020 in foods that our children consume the most. PHE’s recent report, ‘Sugar reduction and wider reformulation programme: Report on progress towards the first 5% reduction and next steps’, shows some good progress. For example, yoghurts have exceeded the first year target and achieved a 6% reduction in sugar.</p><p> </p><p>The soft drinks industry levy has seen half of the products that were initially in scope reformulated – that’s equivalent of removing 45 million kilograms of sugar every year.</p><p> </p><p>We are confident industry will continue to reformulate their products and further progress will be made.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-05T13:54:54.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910258/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910258/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910258/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-23","Food: Sugar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that food manufacturers reduce sugar content in their products.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","147441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910259","Department for International Development","false","2018-06-06","<p>This project provided technical assistance to the Ukrainian Ministry of Defence to support modernisation of the accommodation system for Ukrainian military personnel. It supported delivery of the UK’s objective to help Ukraine reform its Defence/armed forces to eliminate corruption and increase civilian oversight and rule of law, strengthening the resilience and stability of the State. The total cost over some 15 months was £414,930. The project successfully delivered its four main outputs: a proposal for a trusted and transparent centralised process for queue management; a policy for new accommodation maintenance, procurement and contracting standards for the Ukraine defence forces; new construction tender requirements and contracting guidelines; and a concept paper for a new defence housing system and detailed reform implementation plan for at least 2 years.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-06-06T15:32:23.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910259/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910259/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910259/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-05-23","Ukraine: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will publish information on the recent programme with the Ukrainian Ministry of Defence Reforms Project Office to develop a housing system for the armed forces of Ukraine; and what the cost to the public purse was of that programme.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","147474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910260","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-06","<p>The British High Commission in Pretoria regularly discusses illegal wildlife trade (IWT) issues with the South African Government and has funded joint projects to increase IWT law enforcement capacity and cooperation in the region. We have also raised this issue at the highest political levels: the Foreign Secretary last discussed IWT with the South African Foreign Minister, Lindiwe Sisulu, during a bilateral meeting on 17 April. In addition, the Foreign Secretary took advantage of the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting to remind his Commonwealth opposite numbers of the importance of the counter-IWT agenda in general and in particular of senior attendance at the IWT Conference in London in October. We will continue to build on our partnership with the South African Government, including at the Conference itself.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-06-06T15:53:26.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910260/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910260/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910260/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-23","South Africa: Poaching","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with its counterpart in South Africa on reducing poaching in that country.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","147442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910261","House of Commons Commission","false","2018-06-06","<p>The House of Commons Commission has no plans to pause the recruitment of in-house tour guides because the final decision on the new guiding service was taken several months ago. It has been endorsed by the House of Commons Administration Committee and the Commission. Recruitment of 28 new members of House of Commons staff to take the majority of tours in Parliament will be completed this month.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2018-06-06T10:47:16.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910261/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910261/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910261/answer",,,,,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2018-05-23","Parliamentary Tours","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, with reference to the ongoing discussions in the Administration Committee on the future of Blue Badge guided tours of the House, what the Commission's policy is on pausing the recruitment of in-house staff pending a final decision on the guiding service.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","147401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910262","Department for International Trade","false","2018-06-04","<p>The Government voted against the EU Modernisation of Trade Defence Instruments due to the proposed restrictions to the Lesser Duty Rule. The Lesser Duty Rule provides producers with robust and proportionate protections they need against unfair trade from dumped and subsidised imports, but without imposing punitive measures that could harm downstream users or consumers.</p><p> </p><p>Our view is that the Lesser Duty Rule helps to balance the interests of all and that limiting it will mean increased costs, with no evidence of benefits.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-06-04T16:03:30.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910262/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910262/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910262/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-05-23","EU Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, for what reasons the Government voted against the proposed Modernisation of Trade Defence Instruments in the EU Council on 16 April 2018.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","147496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910263","Leader of the House","false","2018-06-04","<p>I am grateful to the Procedure Committee for its work on proxy voting and the proposals that they have made in their report. The Government is currently considering the recommendations in detail and will respond to the report in due course.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2018-06-04T09:48:32.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910263/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910263/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910263/answer",,,,,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2018-05-23","Absent Voting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, whether she plans to take steps to implement the recommendations of the Fifth Report of the Procedure Committee, Proxy voting and parental absence, published on 9 May 2018, HC 825.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","147298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910264","Home Office","false","2018-06-04","<p>The Home Office does not centrally hold the information requested.</p><p>The Home Office collects and publishes information on the primary roles that police officers perform, as well as the number of frontline officers, for Police Force Areas in England and Wales. Data are collected on a full-time equivalent (FTE) basis, with no information available for the number of hours spent performing each role. These data are published annually as part of the 'police workforce, England and Wales' statistical bulletin, the latest of which can be accessed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-workforce-england-and-wales-31-march-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-workforce-england-and-wales-31-march-2017</a></p><p>Data on the primary roles officers perform, and the number of officers on the frontline, are only collected at Police Force Area level and cannot be broken down any further. Furthermore, the number of officers specifically on foot patrol cannot be separately identified. The latest available data on frontline officers, broken down by Police Force Area and going back to 2010, can be found in Table_F5 of the data tables accompanying the main release.</p><p>Data for the years 2010 to 2014 are estimated since data prior to 31 March 2015 were collected under a different framework, with different definitions.</p><p>Decisions on the size and deployment of the police workforce are operational matters for Chief Officers working with their Police and Crime Commissioners and taking into account local priorities.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-06-04T15:58:09.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910264/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910264/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910264/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Metropolitan Police: Police Patrolling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many hours police officers spent on patrol in (a) the London Borough of Southwark and (b) the Metropolitan Police Service in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","147299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910265","Home Office","false","2018-06-26","<p>The information requested is not held by the Department.</p><p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the Office for National Statistics. The Office for National Statistics has published data on an estimate of the population classified as usually resident in the UK, from National level to Region level in England and Wales, by country of birth and by year of arrival in the UK. The published data can be found on the ONS website at: <br><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/populationandmigration/internationalmigration/adhocs/008406ct08002011censuscobukcaribbeancontinentsbyyrarrivalbypassportnattoregion" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/populationandmigration/internationalmigration/adhocs/008406ct08002011censuscobukcaribbeancontinentsbyyrarrivalbypassportnattoregion</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-06-26T13:43:40.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910265/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910265/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910265/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Windrush Generation: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate her Department has made of the number of people from the Windrush Generation who live in (a) Camberwell and Peckham constituency, (b) the London Borough of Southwark and (c) London.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","147300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910266","Home Office","false","2018-06-04","<p>The information requested could only be supplied at disproportionate cost.</p><p>Home Office data is not broken down by Parliamentary constituency or metropolitan borough. The latest data, which goes back to 2009, is published in ‘Immigration Statistics, October to December 2017’, and is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/681703/detention-oct-dec-2017-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/681703/detention-oct-dec-2017-tables.ods</a>.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-06-04T16:32:48.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910266/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910266/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910266/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-23","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many residents have been detained in immigration detention centres with issues outstanding from (a) the constituency of Camberwell and Peckham and (b) the London Borough of Southwark in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","147301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910267","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-06-04","<p>The Ministry of Defence has regular discussions with the US F-35 Joint Program Office on all aspects of the F-35 programme to ensure that the UK is ready to receive its F-35 aircraft. The UK is fully equipped to safely and securely hold software relating to the F-35.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-06-04T16:00:54.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910267/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910267/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910267/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-23","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with his US counterpart on clearing UK sites to hold software relating to F-35.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","147402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910268","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-04","<p>Due to internal changes and restructuring during the time period in question, there is no comparable data available at departmental directorate level. However, the number of full time equivalent employees in my Department in each year since 2010 was as follows:</p><p>2009-10 – 2108.7</p><p>2010-11 – 1934.1</p><p>2011-12 – 1821.6</p><p>2012-13 – 1680.9</p><p>2013-14 – 1622.0</p><p>2014-15 – 1595.7</p><p>2015-16 – 1651.5</p><p>2016-17 – 1410.6</p><p>2017-18 – 1672.3</p><p>We have a forecast figure for 2018-19 of 2002.7 full time equivalent staff but do not have forecast figures for future years at this point in time.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-06-04T14:55:49.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910268/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910268/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910268/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-23","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many full-time equivalent employees his Department (a) has employed in each financial year since 2009-10 (b) is forecast to employ in each financial year until 2020-21 by departmental directorate.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","147328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910269","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-05","<p>Following a successful pilot period, MHCLG’s Recruitment Hub was launched in February 2018. Although we have not set targets, the Hub uses a web-based selection and applicant tracking system designed to reduce management time, improve candidates’ experience and, through name-blind assessment and other techniques, improve the equality of shortlisting decisions. As part of a range of people-related metrics, we monitor the effectiveness of our recruitment and resourcing processes. This includes 'time to hire', which has fallen from an average of 80 days in March 2017 to 65 days in April 2018. We will continue to pursue further process efficiencies.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-06-05T15:24:08.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910269/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910269/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910269/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-23","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to his single departmental plan, what targets he has set to (a) reduce the time it takes to hire, (b) support the introduction of new tools and technology to improve selection and (c) use a new recruitment hub to reduce the administrative burden on vacancy managers.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","147329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910270","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-05","<p>The MHCLG Core Curriculum, which was introduced in July 2016, includes learning that enhances digital, commercial project delivery and management capabilities. We offer a number of internally developed and delivered interventions and Civil Service Learning on-line courses which are signalled as essential learning through the Corporate Induction process.</p><p>Work is underway with the Heads of Professions and their support teams to identify additional foundation and practitioner level learning which will be offered through the Core Curriculum. A clear L&amp;D strategy for each of the three professional areas will be in place by Autumn.</p><p>Work is also on-going to develop an internal programme which will enhance line management capabilities, particularly amongst those who are new to line management and/or the civil service.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-06-05T15:28:42.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910270/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910270/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910270/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-23","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to his single departmental plan, what targets he has set to develop a Core Curriculum with an enhanced focus on digital, commercial, project delivery and line management capabilities.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","147330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910271","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-27","<p>Civil Service wide Diversity targets for entrants to the Senior Civil Service were published on 5 June 2018: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/civil-service-diversity-inclusion-dashboard/civil-service-diversity-and-inclusion-dashboard" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/civil-service-diversity-inclusion-dashboard/civil-service-diversity-and-inclusion-dashboard</a>. MHCLG intends to publish its Department level targets alongside other Government Departments, shortly.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-06-27T14:42:15.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910271/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910271/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910271/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-23","Senior Civil Servants: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to the publication of the single departmental plan 2018, what his targets are for increasing diversity in the Senior Civil Service.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","147331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910272","House of Commons Commission","false","2018-06-06","<p>Redundancy payments for employees of the House of Commons Commission are paid in line with the Civil Service Compensation Scheme rules. These offer an enhanced redundancy payment compared to the statutory requirement but provide specific rules that the House and other “Schedule 1” employers who are part of the Civil Service Pension Arrangements must follow when calculating redundancy payments. House of Commons employees have a contractual entitlement to redundancy payment on these terms and no redundancy payments have been made over and above the Civil Service requirements since 2009. That includes Speaker’s Office staff who are employees of the Commission.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","147444","2018-06-06T10:49:47.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910272/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910272/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910272/answer",,,,,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2018-05-23","House of Commons: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, what estimate the Commission has made of cost to the public purse of redundancy payments over and above the statutory contractual requirement for house staff since 2009.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","147443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910273","House of Commons Commission","false","2018-06-06","<p>Redundancy payments for employees of the House of Commons Commission are paid in line with the Civil Service Compensation Scheme rules. These offer an enhanced redundancy payment compared to the statutory requirement but provide specific rules that the House and other “Schedule 1” employers who are part of the Civil Service Pension Arrangements must follow when calculating redundancy payments. House of Commons employees have a contractual entitlement to redundancy payment on these terms and no redundancy payments have been made over and above the Civil Service requirements since 2009. That includes Speaker’s Office staff who are employees of the Commission.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","147443","2018-06-06T10:49:47.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910273/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910273/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910273/answer",,,,,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2018-05-23","House of Commons: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, what estimate the Commission has made of the cost to the public purse of redundancy payments over and above the statutory contractual requirement for house staff working in the Speaker's office since 2009.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","147444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910274","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-06","<p>The Affordable Homes Programme is £9.1 billion, with £700 million currently allocated to 2021/22.</p><p>The £700 million in 2021/22 includes the £300 million allocated to the Greater London Authority at Spring Statement 2018 and an additional £400 million to cover the money allocated to fund cladding remediation, which the Prime Minister announced on 16 May.</p><p>The extension of the programme responds to calls from the sector for longer term certainty on grant funding.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-06-06T15:15:34.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910274/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910274/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910274/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-23","Affordable Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how much in grant funding will be allocated to the building of affordable housing between 2016 and 2021.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","147332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910275","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-06-04","<p>At Spring Statement 2018 the Chancellor announced an additional £1.67 billion for the GLA to deliver an additional 26,000 affordable homes in London, bringing the total affordable housing budget for London to £4.8 billion to deliver 116,000 over six years. The approach to the remaining money in the programme will be announced shortly.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-06-04T11:27:39.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910275/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910275/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/910275/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-23","Affordable Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether the additional £2 billion in affordable housing funding announced on 4 October 2017 has been allocated.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","147333"
